original_metadata.solution:
Since $\triangle ABE$ is equilateral, we know that $\angle ABE=60^\circ.$ Therefore, \begin{align*}
\angle PBC &= \angle ABC - \angle ABE \\
&= 90^\circ-60^\circ \\
&=30^\circ.
\end{align*} Since $AB=BC,$ we know that $\triangle ABC$ is a right isosceles triangle and $$\angle BAC=\angle BCA=45^\circ.$$ Then, $\angle BCP =\angle BCA=45^\circ$ and \begin{align*}
\angle BPC &= 180^\circ-\angle PBC - \angle BCP \\
&= 180^\circ - 30^\circ - 45^\circ \\
&=\boxed{105^\circ}.
\end{align*}

Using the quadratic formula, we find that the roots of the quadratic are $\frac{-5\pm\sqrt{5^2-4(3)(k)}}{6}=\frac{-5\pm\sqrt{25-12k}}{6}$. Since the problem tells us that these roots must equal $\frac{-5\pm i\sqrt{11}}{6}$, we have \begin{align*} \sqrt{25-12k}&=i\sqrt{11}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad \sqrt{25-12k}&=\sqrt{-11}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 25-12k&=-11
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 12k&=36
\\\Rightarrow\qquad k&=\boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

